# NEOX Minimal Process Model

This document defines the initial process model for NEOX, a minimal UNIX-like operating system for the NEO6502-MMU platform.

The design is intentionally simple and aligned with:

* W65C02 CPU constraints
* RP2350 supervisor model
* MMU-based memory contexts
* mailbox-driven I/O

---

## 1. Design Principles

* minimal and inspectable implementation
* explicit control flow
* no hidden runtime behavior
* incremental complexity

Initial focus:

> processes first, threads later

---

## 2. Execution Model

* single 6502 CPU
* one running process at a time
* cooperative multitasking
* no preemption in v1

A process switch only occurs when:

* `yield` is called
* a syscall blocks
* a process exits

---

## 3. Process Definition

A process consists of:

* one 64K virtual address space (via MMU)
* one saved CPU context
* one process descriptor
* one file descriptor table
* one execution stream

v1 restriction:

> one thread per process

---

## 4. Process States

```
FREE
READY
RUNNING
BLOCKED
ZOMBIE
```

Descriptions:

* FREE: unused slot
* READY: runnable
* RUNNING: currently executing
* BLOCKED: waiting for event
* ZOMBIE: exited, awaiting collection

---

## 5. Process Descriptor

```
struct proc_t
{
    uint8_t state;
    uint8_t pid;
    uint8_t parent_pid;
    uint8_t flags;

    uint16_t ctx_ptr;
    uint8_t mmu_context;
    uint16_t fd_table_ptr;

    uint8_t wait_reason;
    uint8_t exit_code;
};
```

---

## 6. CPU Context

```
struct cpu_ctx_t
{
    uint8_t a;
    uint8_t x;
    uint8_t y;
    uint8_t p;
    uint8_t sp;
    uint8_t pcl;
    uint8_t pch;
};
```

This context is saved/restored during a process switch.

---

## 7. Address Space Model

Each process owns an MMU context.

Shared regions:

* syscall table at `$C000`
* MMU I/O page `$D000-$DFFF`

Process-private regions:

* code
* data
* stack

---

## 8. Scheduling

v1 scheduler:

* cooperative
* round-robin

Simple ready queue:

```
ready_head
ready_tail
ready_q[NPROC]
```

---

## 9. Process Switching

Switch sequence:

1. save CPU context
2. update state
3. select next READY process
4. switch MMU context
5. restore CPU context
6. resume execution

---

## 10. Blocking Model

A process becomes BLOCKED when:

* waiting for console input
* waiting for RP2350 service
* waiting for child process (future)

---

## 11. Required Syscalls

Minimal set:

* `yield`
* `exec`
* `exit`
* `wait`

Behavior:

* `yield`: relinquish CPU
* `exec`: load new program
* `exit`: terminate process
* `wait`: collect child status

---

## 12. Thread Model (Future)

Threads are not part of v1.

Future model:

* multiple execution contexts per process
* shared address space
* shared resources

---

## 13. UNIX-like Scope

NEOX aims to provide:

* process abstraction
* file descriptor I/O
* syscall interface
* blocking semantics

Not required initially:

* POSIX completeness
* signals
* full libc

---

## 14. Implementation Phases

Phase 1:

* process table
* single process
* scheduler skeleton

Phase 2:

* multiple READY processes
* context switching

Phase 3:

* blocking syscalls
* scheduler interaction

Phase 4:

* exec / exit / wait

Phase 5:

* threading (optional)

---

## 15. Summary

A NEOX process in v1 is:

> one MMU context, one CPU state, one execution stream

This model is sufficient to build a minimal, UNIX-like multitasking system on the NEO6502-MMU platform.
